'active_lock_reason': None, 'body': "When examining tables using `cbt`, it would be very handy to be able to list keys only without potentially very large cell values.

This could be done by adding an argument `keys-only` for the `read` command to suppress printing of cell values.

Thus, something like:
```
cbt --project test_project --instance test_instance \
    read \
    test_table \
    count=10 \
    keys-only=true \
    start=$'start_prefix\x1Fsub_prefix'
```

'updated_at': '2022-04-22T15:47:31Z', 'closed_at': '2022-04-22T15:47:31Z', 'author_association': 'CONTRIBUTOR', 'active_lock_reason': None, 'body': "Bigtable has a very flexible data model and every value stored is simply an opaque byte array. Users often store data in a particular way, often in some binary encoded from. This makes cbt’s “read” commands much less useful, since values can only be printed as binary strings. To solve this we want to introduce a command-line option that specifies the format that cbt should use to display the data. This functionality should be available for the “lookup” and “read” commands.

Formatting should initially be controlled via a YAML configuration file supplied via a command-line option.

Formats (beyond the existing/default %q format):

- deserialized protocol-buffer data
- deserialized binary data (e.g. big-endian int64)
- hex

I'll be submitting a PR soon. :)", 'reactions': {'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/googleapis/google-cloud-go/issues/4265/reactions', 'total_count': 0, '+1': 0, '-1': 0, 'laugh': 0, 'hooray': 0, 'confused': 0, 'heart': 0, 'rocket': 0, 'eyes': 0}, 'timeline_url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/googleapis/google-cloud-go/issues/4265/timeline', 'performed_via_github_app': None}}

'updated_at': '2022-04-22T15:47:31Z', 'closed_at': '2022-04-22T15:47:31Z', 'author_association': 'CONTRIBUTOR', 'active_lock_reason': None, 'body': "Bigtable has a very flexible data model and every value stored is simply an opaque byte array. Users often store data in a particular way, often in some binary encoded from. This makes cbt’s “read” commands much less useful, since values can only be printed as binary strings. To solve this we want to introduce a command-line option that specifies the format that cbt should use to display the data. This functionality should be available for the “lookup” and “read” commands.

Formatting should initially be controlled via a YAML configuration file supplied via a command-line option.

Formats (beyond the existing/default %q format):

- deserialized protocol-buffer data
- deserialized binary data (e.g. big-endian int64)
- hex

I'll be submitting a PR soon. :)", 'reactions': {'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/googleapis/google-cloud-go/issues/4265/reactions', 'total_count': 0, '+1': 0, '-1': 0, 'laugh': 0, 'hooray': 0, 'confused': 0, 'heart': 0, 'rocket': 0, 'eyes': 0}, 'timeline_url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/googleapis/google-cloud-go/issues/4265/timeline', 'performed_via_github_app': None}, 'comment': {'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/googleapis/google-cloud-go/issues/comments/1106642196', 'html_url': 'https://github.com/googleapis/google-cloud-go/issues/4265#issuecomment-1106642196', 'issue_url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/googleapis/google-cloud-go/issues/4265', 'id': 1106642196, 'node_id': 'IC_kwDOASszys5B9gUU', 'user': {'login': 'telpirion', 'id': 7399197, 'node_id': 'MDQ6VXNlcjczOTkxOTc=', 'avatar_url': 'https://avatars.githubusercontent.com/u/7399197?v=4', 'gravatar_id': '', 'url': 'https://api.github.com/users/telpirion', 'html_url': 'https://github.com/telpirion', 'followers_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/telpirion/followers', 'following_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/telpirion/following{/other_user}', 'gists_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/telpirion/gists{/gist_id}', 'starred_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/telpirion/starred{/owner}{/repo}', 'subscriptions_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/telpirion/subscriptions', 'organizations_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/telpirion/orgs', 'repos_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/telpirion/repos', 'events_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/telpirion/events{/privacy}', 'received_events_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/telpirion/received_events', 'type': 'User', 'site_admin': False}, 'created_at': '2022-04-22T15:47:31Z', 'updated_at': '2022-04-22T15:47:31Z', 'author_association': 'CONTRIBUTOR', 'body': 'This feature has been implemented in `cbt` version 0.12.0. 'updated_at': '2022-04-22T15:46:06Z', 'closed_at': '2022-04-22T15:46:06Z', 'author_association': 'NONE', 'active_lock_reason': None, 'body': "Currently cbt uses `%q` formatting option to print the cell value, e.g. when using `cbt lookup`. See `printRow` function here: https://github.com/googleapis/google-cloud-go/blob/766638c7c6d3e45b00ec41b4bc55b61fe6908449/bigtable/cmd/cbt/cbt.go#L1022 This is mildly inconvenient, because the result produced by `%q` is Golang-specific, and it's difficult to use it in other environments (like shell or Python). 

It would be more convenient to use something neutral like `%x`, because hex encoding is much more widespread. For example, when the value of the cell is a protobuf message, and one wants to represent it as something human-readable, one needs to get hold of the actual bytes. Getting to bytes from hex encoding is as easy as calling `xxd`, but getting to bytes from `%q` encoding requires Golang, which is not as widely spread. Base64 would work as well.

P.S. it would be even more awesome to get the support for printing the human-readable protobuf messages (akin to `protoc --decode` or at least `protoc --decode-raw`), but that's probably too far fetched for a feature request?

P.P.S. if it's just about changing `%q` to `%x` or switching to base64, I can totally send a PR if it helps, just let me know.", 'reactions': {'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/googleapis/google-cloud-go/issues/2680/reactions', 'total_count': 2, '+1': 2, '-1': 0, 'laugh': 0, 'hooray': 0, 'confused': 0, 'heart': 0, 'rocket': 0, 'eyes': 0}, 'timeline_url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/googleapis/google-cloud-go/issues/2680/timeline', 'performed_via_github_app': None}, 'comment': {'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/googleapis/google-cloud-go/issues/comments/1106641066', 'html_url': 'https://github.com/googleapis/google-cloud-go/issues/2680#issuecomment-1106641066', 'issue_url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/googleapis/google-cloud-go/issues/2680', 'id': 1106641066, 'node_id': 'IC_kwDOASszys5B9gCq', 'user': {'login': 'telpirion', 'id': 7399197, 'node_id': 'MDQ6VXNlcjczOTkxOTc=', 'avatar_url': 'https://avatars.githubusercontent.com/u/7399197?v=4', 'gravatar_id': '', 'url': 'https://api.github.com/users/telpirion', 'html_url': 'https://github.com/telpirion', 'followers_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/telpirion/followers', 'following_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/telpirion/following{/other_user}', 'gists_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/telpirion/gists{/gist_id}', 'starred_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/telpirion/starred{/owner}{/repo}', 'subscriptions_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/telpirion/subscriptions', 'organizations_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/telpirion/orgs', 'repos_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/telpirion/repos', 'events_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/telpirion/events{/privacy}', 'received_events_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/telpirion/received_events', 'type': 'User', 'site_admin': False}, 'created_at': '2022-04-22T15:46:06Z', 'updated_at': '2022-04-22T15:46:06Z', 'author_association': 'CONTRIBUTOR', 'body': 'This feature has been implemented in `cbt` release # 0.12.0. 'active_lock_reason': None, 'body': '## Client
Cloud Bigtable cbt cli client.

## Describe Your Environment
- gcloud project, with a limited [session length] (https://gsuiteupdates.googleblog.com/2019/09/session-length-for-google-cloud-console-login.html) of 2 mins and a  re-authentication method of security key
- gcloud auth login email-from-domain
- gcloud config set project my-project

## Expected Behavior
After waiting for more than 2 minutes, running a cbt command
`cbt listinstances`
cbt should print a message like "You do not currently have an active account selected." 

## Actual Behavior

Instead cbt prints  `Missing -project`

I think the underlying issue is that we are not detecting errors from config-helper:
https://github.com/googleapis/google-cloud-go/blob/be07a624a2e4501df135ab7f731b7cfb408d9df2/bigtable/internal/cbtconfig/cbtconfig.go#L213-L225

See b/130751317 for the original bug report.', 'reactions': {'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/googleapis/google-cloud-go/issues/1695/reactions', 'total_count': 0, '+1': 0, '-1': 0, 'laugh': 0, 'hooray': 0, 'confused': 0, 'heart': 0, 'rocket': 0, 'eyes': 0}, 'timeline_url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/googleapis/google-cloud-go/issues/1695/timeline', 'performed_via_github_app': None}}

'active_lock_reason': None, 'body': '## Client
Cloud Bigtable cbt cli client.

## Describe Your Environment
- gcloud project, with a limited [session length] (https://gsuiteupdates.googleblog.com/2019/09/session-length-for-google-cloud-console-login.html) of 2 mins and a  re-authentication method of security key
- gcloud auth login email-from-domain
- gcloud config set project my-project

## Expected Behavior
After waiting for more than 2 minutes, running a cbt command
`cbt listinstances`
cbt should print a message like "You do not currently have an active account selected." 

## Actual Behavior

Instead cbt prints  `Missing -project`

I think the underlying issue is that we are not detecting errors from config-helper:
https://github.com/googleapis/google-cloud-go/blob/be07a624a2e4501df135ab7f731b7cfb408d9df2/bigtable/internal/cbtconfig/cbtconfig.go#L213-L225

'updated_at': '2022-04-18T16:56:03Z', 'closed_at': '2022-04-18T16:56:03Z', 'author_association': 'NONE', 'active_lock_reason': None, 'body': '**Client**
Bigtable

**Environment**
MacOS

**Go Environment**

go version go1.17 darwin/amd64

**Code**
```go
...init bigtable client
tbl := client.Open(tbl)
row, err := tbl.ReadRow(ctx, "randomkey", bigtable.RowFilter(bigtable.LatestNFilter(2)))
```

**Expected behavior**
`table.ReadRow()` should return a zero-length map and `nil` error according to the docs.
`ReadRow is a convenience implementation of a single-row reader. A missing row will return a zero-length map and a nil error.`

**Actual behavior**
A `nil` map and `nil` error is returned

**Additional context**
This can be either solved by initialising an empty map in `ReadRow()`, or modifiying the docs to specifiy it returns a nil instead.

the following errors:

- Undefined keyword argument `transform`
- Undefined keyword argument `target_transform`
- Undefined variable `root`

Until we fix the issue with the client library, we need to use the Go HTTP client to explicitly make GET/POST requests and not use the client library.

+	ctx := context.Background()
+
+	// The Healthcare API endpoint, API version, and request path.
+	name := fmt.Sprintf("https://healthcare.googleapis.com/v1/projects/%s/locations/%s/datasets/%s/fhirStores/%s/fhir/%s/_search", projectID, location, datasetID, fhirStoreID, resourceType)
+
+	// DefaultClient returns an HTTP Client that uses the
+	// DefaultTokenSource (Application Default Credentials)
+	// to obtain authentication credentials.
+	client, err := google.DefaultClient(ctx, "https://www.googleapis.com/auth/cloud-platform")
+	if err != nil {
+		log.Fatal(err)
+	}
+
+	// NewRequest takes an io.Reader as its third argument,
+	// but the POST request to search for FHIR resources does
+	// not pass any data in its body.
+	req, err := http.NewRequest(http.MethodPost, name, nil)
+
+	// To set additional parameters for search filtering, append the
+	// search terms as query parameters, then assign the encoded
+	// query string to the request.
+	// For example, to search for a Patient with the family name "Smith",
+	// specify a Patient resourceType and then set the following:
+	// q := req.URL.Query()
+	// q.Add("family:exact", "Smith")
+	// req.URL.RawQuery = q.Encode()
+
+	if err != nil {
+		return fmt.Errorf("NewRequest: %v", err)
+	}
+
+	// Sets required application/fhir+json header on the request.
+	req.Header.Add("Content-Type", "application/fhir+json")
+

+	if err != nil {
+		return fmt.Errorf("Do: %v", err)
+	}
+
+	defer resp.Body.Close()
+
+	respBytes, err := ioutil.ReadAll(resp.Body)
+	if err != nil {
+		return fmt.Errorf("could not read response: %v", err)
+	}
+

Until we fix the issue with the client library, we need to use the Go HTTP client to explicitly make GET/POST requests and not use the client library.

Our client libraries do not allow for FHIR GET/POST search requests to be set in the HTTP request path, which is required by the FHIR specification. Until we fix the issue with the client library, we need to use the Go HTTP client to explicitly make GET/POST requests and not use the client library.

As part of this PR, since we're just using simple HTTP requests, we can have a separate sample for POST and a separate one for GET.", 'created_at': '2022-03-23T19:24:13Z', 'updated_at': +	}

Our client libraries do not allow for FHIR GET/POST search requests to be set in the HTTP request path, which is required by the FHIR specification. Due to a bug, you can send search requests by specifying a resource type in the request body, but this is an anti-pattern. +	if err != nil {
+		log.Fatal(err)
+	}
+
+	// NewRequest takes an io.Reader as its third argument,
+	// but the POST request to search for FHIR resources does
+	// not pass any data in its body.

+
+	// To set additional parameters for search filtering, append the
+	// search terms as query parameters, then assign the encoded

+		return fmt.Errorf("NewRequest: %v", err)
+	}
+
+	// Sets required application/fhir+json header on the request.

+

{'push_id': 9429654073, 'size': 1, 'distinct_size': 1, 'ref': 'refs/heads/main', 'head': '0d77640e139ead17acee17ac44a6975ef48b110e', 'before': '2be564b29b3ae78b5a585859bb591872ea869769', 'commits': [{'sha': '0d77640e139ead17acee17ac44a6975ef48b110e', 'author': {'email': 'erschmid@google.com', 'name': 'Eric Schmidt'}, 'message': 'feat: adds keys-only filtering (#51)

* feat(bigtable/cmd/cbt): Add keys-only option to lookup and read to avoid fetching and displaying cell values (#4286)

* Refactor a little to make functional testing practical.

Note that tableLike is likely to grow as we test more. :)

* testing helpers

* refactored stdio capture to be in-memory

* Added some assertion functions

* Added getDataFilter and started wiring it into doLookup and doRead

* Finished wireing up getDataFilter to doLookup and doRead

Also, getDataFilter now takes extra filters as optional input,
which is tested in testing doRead.

* Added creds to config to avoid spewing to stderr

* gofmt

* Added missing licence header

* rearranged comments -- build please :)

* Simplify assertNoError using t.Fatalf. doh!

* Refactored (de-refactored :) ) to make diff smaller

* Revert "Refactored (de-refactored :) ) to make diff smaller"

This reverts commit 09164356daaf4913db8c6c3bd7556a7bada65423.

Because there was a reason to factor out filter logic. :)

* Got rid of nested if

By using the original construct.

* simplified expression.

No need for apend because the result is know to have one element.

Co-authored-by: Christopher Wilcox <crwilcox@google.com>
Co-authored-by: Eric Schmidt <erschmid@google.com>

Why to do this:

- In some cases, the current situation results in a lot of duplicated call (e.g. `doLookup()` and `doRead()`).
- Each `do*()` method has multiple concerns--arg parsing and composing the calls to the service. This breaks the principle of orthogonality.

* Refactor a little to make functional testing practical.

Note that tableLike is likely to grow as we test more. :)

* testing helpers

* refactored stdio capture to be in-memory

* Added some assertion functions

* Added getDataFilter and started wiring it into doLookup and doRead

* Finished wireing up getDataFilter to doLookup and doRead

Also, getDataFilter now takes extra filters as optional input,
which is tested in testing doRead.

* Added creds to config to avoid spewing to stderr

* gofmt

* Added missing licence header

* rearranged comments -- build please :)

* Simplify assertNoError using t.Fatalf. doh!

* Refactored (de-refactored :) ) to make diff smaller

* Revert "Refactored (de-refactored :) ) to make diff smaller"

Because there was a reason to factor out filter logic. :)

* Got rid of nested if

By using the original construct.

* simplified expression.

No need for apend because the result is know to have one element.

### Release Notes

<details>
<summary>grpc/grpc-go</summary>

### [`v1.45.0`](https://togithub.com/grpc/grpc-go/releases/v1.45.0)

[Compare Source](https://togithub.com/grpc/grpc-go/compare/v1.44.0...v1.45.0)

### Bug Fixes

-   xds/clusterresolver: pass cluster name to DNS child policy to be used in creds handshake ([#​5119](https://togithub.com/grpc/grpc-go/issues/5119))
-   reflection: support dynamic messages ([#​5180](https://togithub.com/grpc/grpc-go/issues/5180))
    -   Special Thanks: [@​codebutler](https://togithub.com/codebutler)

### Performance Improvements

-   wrr: improve randomWRR performance ([#​5067](https://togithub.com/grpc/grpc-go/issues/5067))
    -   Special Thanks: [@​huangchong94](https://togithub.com/huangchong94)

### Behavior Changes

-   server: convert context errors returned by service handlers to status with the correct status code (`Canceled` or `DeadlineExceeded`), instead of `Unknown` ([#​5156](https://togithub.com/grpc/grpc-go/issues/5156))

### New Features

-   reflection: add `NewServer(ServerOptions)` for creating a reflection server with advanced customizations ([#​5197](https://togithub.com/grpc/grpc-go/issues/5197))
-   xds: support federation ([#​5128](https://togithub.com/grpc/grpc-go/issues/5128))
-   xds/resource: accept Self as LDS's RDS config source and CDS's EDS config source ([#​5152](https://togithub.com/grpc/grpc-go/issues/5152))
-   xds/bootstrap: add plugin system for credentials specified in bootstrap file ([#​5136](https://togithub.com/grpc/grpc-go/issues/5136))

</details>

Some recurring observations:

+ Similar to above, a lot of err checks happen as local variables within an if block. I think it's easier to read to have the err check follow the assignment of the err, but I think that's a preference thing.

Some recurring observations:

+ A lot of structs are instantiated as literals inside of the methods where they're used. Although this makes for more terse code, it also makes it harder to read for customers. I recommend breaking instantiations outside of method calls so that they're easier to read & understand.
+ Similar to above, a lot of err checks happen as local variables within an if block. I think it's easier to read to have the err check follow the assignment of the err, but I think that's a preference thing.
+ Several sections have multiple things happening at once: a client method call, an error check, and a function declaration all within 1-2 lines. It's harder to parse what's going on with so much happening. I recommend breaking some of these lines into multiple statements.", 'commit_id': '1dc430ff8978b816619810c5351ad922e237aec7', 'submitted_at': '2022-03-15T18:25:33Z', 'state': 'commented', 'html_url': +func TestPgCreateDatabase(t *testing.T) {
+	_ = testutil.SystemTest(t)
+	t.Parallel()
+
+	_, dbName, cleanup := initTest(t, randomID())
+	defer cleanup()
+
+	ctx, cancel := context.WithTimeout(context.Background(), time.Hour)
+	defer cancel()
+	out := runSampleWithContext(ctx, t, pgCreateDatabase, dbName, "failed to create a Spanner PG database")
+	assertContains(t, out, fmt.Sprintf("Created Spanner PostgreSQL database [%s]", dbName))
+}
+
+func TestPgQueryParameter(t *testing.T) {
+	_ = testutil.SystemTest(t)
+	t.Parallel()
+
+	_, dbName, cleanup := initTest(t, randomID())
+	defer cleanup()
+	dbCleanup, err := createTestPgDatabase(
+		dbName,
+		`CREATE TABLE Singers (
+		   SingerId  bigint NOT NULL PRIMARY KEY,
+		   FirstName varchar(1024),
+		   LastName  varchar(1024)
+		 )`)
+	if dbCleanup != nil {
+		defer dbCleanup()
+	}
+	if err != nil {
+		t.Fatalf("failed to create test database: %v", err)
+	}
+	client, err := spanner.NewClient(context.Background(), dbName)
+	if err != nil {
+		t.Fatalf("failed to create Spanner client: %v", err)
+	}
+	if _, err := client.Apply(context.Background(), []*spanner.Mutation{
+		spanner.InsertOrUpdateMap("Singers", map[string]interface{}{
+			"SingerId":  1,
+			"FirstName": "Bruce",
+			"LastName":  "Allison",
+		}),
+		spanner.InsertOrUpdateMap("Singers", map[string]interface{}{
+			"SingerId":  2,
+			"FirstName": "Alice",
+			"LastName":  "Bruxelles",
+		}),
+	}); err != nil {
+		t.Fatalf("failed to insert test records: %v", err)
+	}
+
+	out := runSample(t, pgQueryParameter, dbName, "failed to execute PG query with parameter")
+	assertContains(t, out, "1 Bruce Allison")
+	assertNotContains(t, out, "2 Alice Bruxelles")
+}

+func TestPgInformationSchema(t *testing.T) {
+	_ = testutil.SystemTest(t)
+	t.Parallel()
+
+	_, dbName, cleanup := initTest(t, randomID())
+	defer cleanup()
+	dbCleanup, err := createTestPgDatabase(dbName)
+	if dbCleanup != nil {
+		defer dbCleanup()
+	}
+	if err != nil {
+		t.Fatalf("failed to create test database: %v", err)
+	}
+
+	matches := regexp.MustCompile("^(.*)/databases/(.*)$").FindStringSubmatch(dbName)

+		t.Fatalf("Invalid database id %s", dbName)
+	}

+	assertContains(t, out, fmt.Sprintf("Table: %s.public.venues (User defined type: null)", matches[2]))
+}

+	}

+		return err
+	}

+// pgNumericDataType shows how to work with the PostgreSQL NUMERIC/DECIMAL data
+// type on a Spanner PostgreSQL database.
+func pgNumericDataType(w io.Writer, db string) error {
+	// db := "projects/my-project/instances/my-instance/databases/my-database"
+	ctx := context.Background()
+
+	adminClient, err := database.NewDatabaseAdminClient(ctx)
+	if err != nil {
+		return err
+	}
+	defer adminClient.Close()
+
+	// Create a table that includes a column with data type NUMERIC. As the database has been
+	// created with the PostgreSQL dialect, the data type that is used will be the PostgreSQL
+	// NUMERIC / DECIMAL data type.
+	op, err := adminClient.UpdateDatabaseDdl(ctx, &adminpb.UpdateDatabaseDdlRequest{
+		Database: db,
+		Statements: []string{
+			`CREATE TABLE Venues (
+				VenueId  bigint NOT NULL PRIMARY KEY,
+				Name     varchar(1024) NOT NULL,
+				Revenues numeric
+			)`},
+	})
+	if err != nil {
+		return err
+	}
+	if err := op.Wait(ctx); err != nil {
+		return err
+	}
+	fmt.Fprintf(w, "Created Venues table\n")
+
+	client, err := spanner.NewClient(ctx, db)
+	if err != nil {
+		return err
+	}
+	defer client.Close()
+

+			},
+		})
+		return err
+	})
+	if err != nil {
+		return err
+	}
+	fmt.Fprintf(w, "Inserted %d venue(s)\n", updateCount)
+

+// pgNumericDataType shows how to work with the PostgreSQL NUMERIC/DECIMAL data
+// type on a Spanner PostgreSQL database.
+func pgNumericDataType(w io.Writer, db string) error {
+	// db := "projects/my-project/instances/my-instance/databases/my-database"
+	ctx := context.Background()
+
+	adminClient, err := database.NewDatabaseAdminClient(ctx)
+	if err != nil {
+		return err
+	}
+	defer adminClient.Close()
+
+	// Create a table that includes a column with data type NUMERIC. As the database has been
+	// created with the PostgreSQL dialect, the data type that is used will be the PostgreSQL
+	// NUMERIC / DECIMAL data type.
+	op, err := adminClient.UpdateDatabaseDdl(ctx, &adminpb.UpdateDatabaseDdlRequest{
+		Database: db,
+		Statements: []string{
+			`CREATE TABLE Venues (
+				VenueId  bigint NOT NULL PRIMARY KEY,
+				Name     varchar(1024) NOT NULL,
+				Revenues numeric
+			)`},
+	})
+	if err != nil {
+		return err
+	}
+	if err := op.Wait(ctx); err != nil {
+		return err
+	}
+	fmt.Fprintf(w, "Created Venues table\n")
+
+	client, err := spanner.NewClient(ctx, db)
+	if err != nil {
+		return err
+	}
+	defer client.Close()
+
+	var updateCount int64
+	// Insert a Venue using DML.
+	_, err = client.ReadWriteTransaction(ctx, func(ctx context.Context, transaction *spanner.ReadWriteTransaction) error {
+		updateCount, err = transaction.Update(ctx, spanner.Statement{
+			SQL: `INSERT INTO Venues (VenueId, Name, Revenues) VALUES ($1, $2, $3)`,
+			Params: map[string]interface{}{
+				"p1": 1,
+				"p2": "Venue 1",
+				"p3": spanner.PGNumeric{Numeric: "3150.25", Valid: true},
+			},
+		})
+		return err
+	})
+	if err != nil {
+		return err
+	}
+	fmt.Fprintf(w, "Inserted %d venue(s)\n", updateCount)

+				SingerId  bigint NOT NULL PRIMARY KEY,
+				-- FirstName and LastName are double-quoted and will therefore retain their
+				-- mixed case and are case-sensitive. This means that any statement that
+				-- references any of these columns must use double quotes.
+				"FirstName" varchar(1024) NOT NULL,

+func TestPgCreateDatabase(t *testing.T) {
+	_ = testutil.SystemTest(t)
+	t.Parallel()
+
+	_, dbName, cleanup := initTest(t, randomID())
+	defer cleanup()
+
+	ctx, cancel := context.WithTimeout(context.Background(), time.Hour)
+	defer cancel()
+	out := runSampleWithContext(ctx, t, pgCreateDatabase, dbName, "failed to create a Spanner PG database")
+	assertContains(t, out, fmt.Sprintf("Created Spanner PostgreSQL database [%s]", dbName))
+}
+
+func TestPgQueryParameter(t *testing.T) {
+	_ = testutil.SystemTest(t)
+	t.Parallel()
+
+	_, dbName, cleanup := initTest(t, randomID())
+	defer cleanup()
+	dbCleanup, err := createTestPgDatabase(
+		dbName,
+		`CREATE TABLE Singers (
+		   SingerId  bigint NOT NULL PRIMARY KEY,
+		   FirstName varchar(1024),
+		   LastName  varchar(1024)
+		 )`)
+	if dbCleanup != nil {
+		defer dbCleanup()
+	}
+	if err != nil {
+		t.Fatalf("failed to create test database: %v", err)
+	}
+	client, err := spanner.NewClient(context.Background(), dbName)
+	if err != nil {
+		t.Fatalf("failed to create Spanner client: %v", err)
+	}
+	if _, err := client.Apply(context.Background(), []*spanner.Mutation{
+		spanner.InsertOrUpdateMap("Singers", map[string]interface{}{
+			"SingerId":  1,
+			"FirstName": "Bruce",
+			"LastName":  "Allison",
+		}),
+		spanner.InsertOrUpdateMap("Singers", map[string]interface{}{
+			"SingerId":  2,
+			"FirstName": "Alice",
+			"LastName":  "Bruxelles",
+		}),
+	}); err != nil {
+		t.Fatalf("failed to insert test records: %v", err)
+	}
+
+	out := runSample(t, pgQueryParameter, dbName, "failed to execute PG query with parameter")
+	assertContains(t, out, "1 Bruce Allison")
+	assertNotContains(t, out, "2 Alice Bruxelles")
+}

+			user_name varchar(1024),
+			active    boolean
+		)`)

+		defer dbCleanup()
+	}
+	if err != nil {
+		t.Fatalf("failed to create test database: %v", err)
+	}
+	client, err := spanner.NewClient(context.Background(), dbName)
+	if err != nil {
+		t.Fatalf("failed to create Spanner client: %v", err)
+	}
+	if _, err := client.Apply(context.Background(), []*spanner.Mutation{
+		spanner.InsertOrUpdateMap("users", map[string]interface{}{
+			"user_id":   1,
+			"user_name": "User 1",
+			"active":    false,
+		}),
+		spanner.InsertOrUpdateMap("users", map[string]interface{}{

+			"user_name": "User 2",
+			"active":    false,
+		}),
+		spanner.InsertOrUpdateMap("users", map[string]interface{}{
+			"user_id":   3,
+			"user_name": "User 3",
+			"active":    true,
+		}),
+	}); err != nil {
+		t.Fatalf("failed to insert test records: %v", err)
+	}
+
+	out := runSample(t, pgPartitionedDml, dbName, "failed to execute PG Partitioned DML sample")
+	assertContains(t, out, "Deleted at least 2 inactive users")
+}

+func TestPgCaseSensitivity(t *testing.T) {
+	_ = testutil.SystemTest(t)
+	t.Parallel()
+
+	_, dbName, cleanup := initTest(t, randomID())
+	defer cleanup()
+	dbCleanup, err := createTestPgDatabase(dbName)
+	if dbCleanup != nil {
+		defer dbCleanup()
+	}
+	if err != nil {
+		t.Fatalf("failed to create test database: %v", err)
+	}
+
+	out := runSample(t, pgCaseSensitivity, dbName, "failed to execute PG case sensitivity sample")
+	assertContains(t, out, "SingerId: 1, FirstName: Bruce, LastName: Allison")
+	assertContains(t, out, "SingerId: 1, FullName: Bruce Allison")
+}

+func TestPgCreateDatabase(t *testing.T) {
+	_ = testutil.SystemTest(t)
+	t.Parallel()
+
+	_, dbName, cleanup := initTest(t, randomID())
+	defer cleanup()
+
+	ctx, cancel := context.WithTimeout(context.Background(), time.Hour)
+	defer cancel()
+	out := runSampleWithContext(ctx, t, pgCreateDatabase, dbName, "failed to create a Spanner PG database")
+	assertContains(t, out, fmt.Sprintf("Created Spanner PostgreSQL database [%s]", dbName))
+}
+
+func TestPgQueryParameter(t *testing.T) {
+	_ = testutil.SystemTest(t)
+	t.Parallel()
+
+	_, dbName, cleanup := initTest(t, randomID())
+	defer cleanup()
+	dbCleanup, err := createTestPgDatabase(
+		dbName,
+		`CREATE TABLE Singers (
+		   SingerId  bigint NOT NULL PRIMARY KEY,
+		   FirstName varchar(1024),
+		   LastName  varchar(1024)
+		 )`)
+	if dbCleanup != nil {
+		defer dbCleanup()
+	}
+	if err != nil {
+		t.Fatalf("failed to create test database: %v", err)
+	}
+	client, err := spanner.NewClient(context.Background(), dbName)
+	if err != nil {
+		t.Fatalf("failed to create Spanner client: %v", err)
+	}
+	if _, err := client.Apply(context.Background(), []*spanner.Mutation{
+		spanner.InsertOrUpdateMap("Singers", map[string]interface{}{
+			"SingerId":  1,
+			"FirstName": "Bruce",
+			"LastName":  "Allison",
+		}),
+		spanner.InsertOrUpdateMap("Singers", map[string]interface{}{
+			"SingerId":  2,
+			"FirstName": "Alice",
+			"LastName":  "Bruxelles",
+		}),
+	}); err != nil {
+		t.Fatalf("failed to insert test records: %v", err)
+	}
+
+	out := runSample(t, pgQueryParameter, dbName, "failed to execute PG query with parameter")
+	assertContains(t, out, "1 Bruce Allison")
+	assertNotContains(t, out, "2 Alice Bruxelles")
+}

+func TestPgCreateDatabase(t *testing.T) {
+	_ = testutil.SystemTest(t)
+	t.Parallel()
+
+	_, dbName, cleanup := initTest(t, randomID())
+	defer cleanup()
+
+	ctx, cancel := context.WithTimeout(context.Background(), time.Hour)
+	defer cancel()
+	out := runSampleWithContext(ctx, t, pgCreateDatabase, dbName, "failed to create a Spanner PG database")
+	assertContains(t, out, fmt.Sprintf("Created Spanner PostgreSQL database [%s]", dbName))
+}
+
+func TestPgQueryParameter(t *testing.T) {
+	_ = testutil.SystemTest(t)
+	t.Parallel()
+
+	_, dbName, cleanup := initTest(t, randomID())
+	defer cleanup()
+	dbCleanup, err := createTestPgDatabase(
+		dbName,
+		`CREATE TABLE Singers (
+		   SingerId  bigint NOT NULL PRIMARY KEY,
+		   FirstName varchar(1024),
+		   LastName  varchar(1024)
+		 )`)
+	if dbCleanup != nil {
+		defer dbCleanup()
+	}
+	if err != nil {
+		t.Fatalf("failed to create test database: %v", err)
+	}
+	client, err := spanner.NewClient(context.Background(), dbName)
+	if err != nil {
+		t.Fatalf("failed to create Spanner client: %v", err)
+	}
+	if _, err := client.Apply(context.Background(), []*spanner.Mutation{
+		spanner.InsertOrUpdateMap("Singers", map[string]interface{}{
+			"SingerId":  1,
+			"FirstName": "Bruce",
+			"LastName":  "Allison",
+		}),
+		spanner.InsertOrUpdateMap("Singers", map[string]interface{}{
+			"SingerId":  2,
+			"FirstName": "Alice",
+			"LastName":  "Bruxelles",
+		}),
+	}); err != nil {
+		t.Fatalf("failed to insert test records: %v", err)
+	}
+
+	out := runSample(t, pgQueryParameter, dbName, "failed to execute PG query with parameter")
+	assertContains(t, out, "1 Bruce Allison")
+	assertNotContains(t, out, "2 Alice Bruxelles")
+}

+func TestPgCreateDatabase(t *testing.T) {
+	_ = testutil.SystemTest(t)
+	t.Parallel()
+
+	_, dbName, cleanup := initTest(t, randomID())
+	defer cleanup()
+
+	ctx, cancel := context.WithTimeout(context.Background(), time.Hour)
+	defer cancel()
+	out := runSampleWithContext(ctx, t, pgCreateDatabase, dbName, "failed to create a Spanner PG database")
+	assertContains(t, out, fmt.Sprintf("Created Spanner PostgreSQL database [%s]", dbName))
+}
+
+func TestPgQueryParameter(t *testing.T) {
+	_ = testutil.SystemTest(t)
+	t.Parallel()
+
+	_, dbName, cleanup := initTest(t, randomID())
+	defer cleanup()
+	dbCleanup, err := createTestPgDatabase(
+		dbName,
+		`CREATE TABLE Singers (
+		   SingerId  bigint NOT NULL PRIMARY KEY,
+		   FirstName varchar(1024),
+		   LastName  varchar(1024)
+		 )`)
+	if dbCleanup != nil {
+		defer dbCleanup()
+	}
+	if err != nil {
+		t.Fatalf("failed to create test database: %v", err)
+	}
+	client, err := spanner.NewClient(context.Background(), dbName)
+	if err != nil {
+		t.Fatalf("failed to create Spanner client: %v", err)
+	}
+	if _, err := client.Apply(context.Background(), []*spanner.Mutation{
+		spanner.InsertOrUpdateMap("Singers", map[string]interface{}{
+			"SingerId":  1,
+			"FirstName": "Bruce",
+			"LastName":  "Allison",
+		}),
+		spanner.InsertOrUpdateMap("Singers", map[string]interface{}{
+			"SingerId":  2,
+			"FirstName": "Alice",
+			"LastName":  "Bruxelles",
+		}),
+	}); err != nil {
+		t.Fatalf("failed to insert test records: %v", err)
+	}
+
+	out := runSample(t, pgQueryParameter, dbName, "failed to execute PG query with parameter")
+	assertContains(t, out, "1 Bruce Allison")
+	assertNotContains(t, out, "2 Alice Bruxelles")
+}
+

+}

+			"FirstName": "Alice",
+			"LastName":  "Bruxelles",
+		}),
+	}); err != nil {
+		t.Fatalf("failed to insert test records: %v", err)
+	}
+
+	out := runSample(t, pgQueryParameter, dbName, "failed to execute PG query with parameter")
+	assertContains(t, out, "1 Bruce Allison")
+	assertNotContains(t, out, "2 Alice Bruxelles")
+}

+func TestPgCreateDatabase(t *testing.T) {
+	_ = testutil.SystemTest(t)
+	t.Parallel()
+
+	_, dbName, cleanup := initTest(t, randomID())
+	defer cleanup()
+
+	ctx, cancel := context.WithTimeout(context.Background(), time.Hour)
+	defer cancel()
+	out := runSampleWithContext(ctx, t, pgCreateDatabase, dbName, "failed to create a Spanner PG database")
+	assertContains(t, out, fmt.Sprintf("Created Spanner PostgreSQL database [%s]", dbName))
+}
+
+func TestPgQueryParameter(t *testing.T) {
+	_ = testutil.SystemTest(t)
+	t.Parallel()
+
+	_, dbName, cleanup := initTest(t, randomID())
+	defer cleanup()
+	dbCleanup, err := createTestPgDatabase(
+		dbName,
+		`CREATE TABLE Singers (
+		   SingerId  bigint NOT NULL PRIMARY KEY,
+		   FirstName varchar(1024),
+		   LastName  varchar(1024)
+		 )`)
+	if dbCleanup != nil {
+		defer dbCleanup()
+	}
+	if err != nil {
+		t.Fatalf("failed to create test database: %v", err)
+	}
+	client, err := spanner.NewClient(context.Background(), dbName)
+	if err != nil {
+		t.Fatalf("failed to create Spanner client: %v", err)
+	}
+	if _, err := client.Apply(context.Background(), []*spanner.Mutation{
+		spanner.InsertOrUpdateMap("Singers", map[string]interface{}{
+			"SingerId":  1,
+			"FirstName": "Bruce",
+			"LastName":  "Allison",
+		}),
+		spanner.InsertOrUpdateMap("Singers", map[string]interface{}{
+			"SingerId":  2,
+			"FirstName": "Alice",
+			"LastName":  "Bruxelles",
+		}),
+	}); err != nil {
+		t.Fatalf("failed to insert test records: %v", err)
+	}
+
+	out := runSample(t, pgQueryParameter, dbName, "failed to execute PG query with parameter")
+	assertContains(t, out, "1 Bruce Allison")
+	assertNotContains(t, out, "2 Alice Bruxelles")
+}
+

+func TestPgCreateDatabase(t *testing.T) {
+	_ = testutil.SystemTest(t)
+	t.Parallel()
+
+	_, dbName, cleanup := initTest(t, randomID())
+	defer cleanup()
+
+	ctx, cancel := context.WithTimeout(context.Background(), time.Hour)
+	defer cancel()
+	out := runSampleWithContext(ctx, t, pgCreateDatabase, dbName, "failed to create a Spanner PG database")
+	assertContains(t, out, fmt.Sprintf("Created Spanner PostgreSQL database [%s]", dbName))
+}
+
+func TestPgQueryParameter(t *testing.T) {
+	_ = testutil.SystemTest(t)
+	t.Parallel()
+
+	_, dbName, cleanup := initTest(t, randomID())
+	defer cleanup()
+	dbCleanup, err := createTestPgDatabase(
+		dbName,
+		`CREATE TABLE Singers (
+		   SingerId  bigint NOT NULL PRIMARY KEY,
+		   FirstName varchar(1024),
+		   LastName  varchar(1024)
+		 )`)
+	if dbCleanup != nil {
+		defer dbCleanup()
+	}
+	if err != nil {
+		t.Fatalf("failed to create test database: %v", err)
+	}
+	client, err := spanner.NewClient(context.Background(), dbName)
+	if err != nil {
+		t.Fatalf("failed to create Spanner client: %v", err)
+	}
+	if _, err := client.Apply(context.Background(), []*spanner.Mutation{
+		spanner.InsertOrUpdateMap("Singers", map[string]interface{}{
+			"SingerId":  1,
+			"FirstName": "Bruce",
+			"LastName":  "Allison",
+		}),
+		spanner.InsertOrUpdateMap("Singers", map[string]interface{}{
+			"SingerId":  2,
+			"FirstName": "Alice",
+			"LastName":  "Bruxelles",
+		}),
+	}); err != nil {
+		t.Fatalf("failed to insert test records: %v", err)
+	}
+
+	out := runSample(t, pgQueryParameter, dbName, "failed to execute PG query with parameter")
+	assertContains(t, out, "1 Bruce Allison")
+	assertNotContains(t, out, "2 Alice Bruxelles")
+}
+

+func TestPgCreateDatabase(t *testing.T) {
+	_ = testutil.SystemTest(t)
+	t.Parallel()
+
+	_, dbName, cleanup := initTest(t, randomID())
+	defer cleanup()
+
+	ctx, cancel := context.WithTimeout(context.Background(), time.Hour)
+	defer cancel()
+	out := runSampleWithContext(ctx, t, pgCreateDatabase, dbName, "failed to create a Spanner PG database")
+	assertContains(t, out, fmt.Sprintf("Created Spanner PostgreSQL database [%s]", dbName))
+}
+
+func TestPgQueryParameter(t *testing.T) {
+	_ = testutil.SystemTest(t)
+	t.Parallel()
+
+	_, dbName, cleanup := initTest(t, randomID())
+	defer cleanup()
+	dbCleanup, err := createTestPgDatabase(
+		dbName,
+		`CREATE TABLE Singers (
+		   SingerId  bigint NOT NULL PRIMARY KEY,
+		   FirstName varchar(1024),
+		   LastName  varchar(1024)
+		 )`)
+	if dbCleanup != nil {
+		defer dbCleanup()
+	}
+	if err != nil {
+		t.Fatalf("failed to create test database: %v", err)
+	}
+	client, err := spanner.NewClient(context.Background(), dbName)
+	if err != nil {
+		t.Fatalf("failed to create Spanner client: %v", err)
+	}
+	if _, err := client.Apply(context.Background(), []*spanner.Mutation{
+		spanner.InsertOrUpdateMap("Singers", map[string]interface{}{
+			"SingerId":  1,
+			"FirstName": "Bruce",
+			"LastName":  "Allison",
+		}),
+		spanner.InsertOrUpdateMap("Singers", map[string]interface{}{
+			"SingerId":  2,
+			"FirstName": "Alice",
+			"LastName":  "Bruxelles",
+		}),
+	}); err != nil {
+		t.Fatalf("failed to insert test records: %v", err)
+	}
+
+	out := runSample(t, pgQueryParameter, dbName, "failed to execute PG query with parameter")
+	assertContains(t, out, "1 Bruce Allison")
+	assertNotContains(t, out, "2 Alice Bruxelles")
+}
+

+func TestPgInformationSchema(t *testing.T) {
+	_ = testutil.SystemTest(t)
+	t.Parallel()
+
+	_, dbName, cleanup := initTest(t, randomID())
+	defer cleanup()
+	dbCleanup, err := createTestPgDatabase(dbName)
+	if dbCleanup != nil {
+		defer dbCleanup()
+	}
+	if err != nil {
+		t.Fatalf("failed to create test database: %v", err)
+	}
+
+	matches := regexp.MustCompile("^(.*)/databases/(.*)$").FindStringSubmatch(dbName)
+	if matches == nil || len(matches) != 3 {
+		t.Fatalf("Invalid database id %s", dbName)
+	}

+	assertContains(t, out, fmt.Sprintf("Table: %s.public.venues (User defined type: null)", matches[2]))
+}

+func TestPgCreateDatabase(t *testing.T) {
+	_ = testutil.SystemTest(t)
+	t.Parallel()
+
+	_, dbName, cleanup := initTest(t, randomID())
+	defer cleanup()
+
+	ctx, cancel := context.WithTimeout(context.Background(), time.Hour)
+	defer cancel()
+	out := runSampleWithContext(ctx, t, pgCreateDatabase, dbName, "failed to create a Spanner PG database")
+	assertContains(t, out, fmt.Sprintf("Created Spanner PostgreSQL database [%s]", dbName))
+}
+
+func TestPgQueryParameter(t *testing.T) {
+	_ = testutil.SystemTest(t)
+	t.Parallel()
+
+	_, dbName, cleanup := initTest(t, randomID())
+	defer cleanup()
+	dbCleanup, err := createTestPgDatabase(
+		dbName,
+		`CREATE TABLE Singers (
+		   SingerId  bigint NOT NULL PRIMARY KEY,
+		   FirstName varchar(1024),
+		   LastName  varchar(1024)
+		 )`)
+	if dbCleanup != nil {
+		defer dbCleanup()
+	}
+	if err != nil {
+		t.Fatalf("failed to create test database: %v", err)
+	}
+	client, err := spanner.NewClient(context.Background(), dbName)
+	if err != nil {
+		t.Fatalf("failed to create Spanner client: %v", err)
+	}
+	if _, err := client.Apply(context.Background(), []*spanner.Mutation{
+		spanner.InsertOrUpdateMap("Singers", map[string]interface{}{
+			"SingerId":  1,
+			"FirstName": "Bruce",
+			"LastName":  "Allison",
+		}),
+		spanner.InsertOrUpdateMap("Singers", map[string]interface{}{
+			"SingerId":  2,
+			"FirstName": "Alice",
+			"LastName":  "Bruxelles",
+		}),
+	}); err != nil {
+		t.Fatalf("failed to insert test records: %v", err)
+	}
+
+	out := runSample(t, pgQueryParameter, dbName, "failed to execute PG query with parameter")
+	assertContains(t, out, "1 Bruce Allison")
+	assertNotContains(t, out, "2 Alice Bruxelles")
+}

+func TestPgCreateDatabase(t *testing.T) {
+	_ = testutil.SystemTest(t)
+	t.Parallel()
+
+	_, dbName, cleanup := initTest(t, randomID())
+	defer cleanup()
+
+	ctx, cancel := context.WithTimeout(context.Background(), time.Hour)
+	defer cancel()
+	out := runSampleWithContext(ctx, t, pgCreateDatabase, dbName, "failed to create a Spanner PG database")
+	assertContains(t, out, fmt.Sprintf("Created Spanner PostgreSQL database [%s]", dbName))
+}
+
+func TestPgQueryParameter(t *testing.T) {
+	_ = testutil.SystemTest(t)
+	t.Parallel()
+
+	_, dbName, cleanup := initTest(t, randomID())
+	defer cleanup()
+	dbCleanup, err := createTestPgDatabase(
+		dbName,
+		`CREATE TABLE Singers (
+		   SingerId  bigint NOT NULL PRIMARY KEY,
+		   FirstName varchar(1024),
+		   LastName  varchar(1024)
+		 )`)
+	if dbCleanup != nil {
+		defer dbCleanup()
+	}
+	if err != nil {
+		t.Fatalf("failed to create test database: %v", err)
+	}
+	client, err := spanner.NewClient(context.Background(), dbName)
+	if err != nil {
+		t.Fatalf("failed to create Spanner client: %v", err)
+	}
+	if _, err := client.Apply(context.Background(), []*spanner.Mutation{
+		spanner.InsertOrUpdateMap("Singers", map[string]interface{}{
+			"SingerId":  1,
+			"FirstName": "Bruce",
+			"LastName":  "Allison",
+		}),
+		spanner.InsertOrUpdateMap("Singers", map[string]interface{}{
+			"SingerId":  2,
+			"FirstName": "Alice",
+			"LastName":  "Bruxelles",
+		}),
+	}); err != nil {
+		t.Fatalf("failed to insert test records: %v", err)
+	}
+
+	out := runSample(t, pgQueryParameter, dbName, "failed to execute PG query with parameter")
+	assertContains(t, out, "1 Bruce Allison")
+	assertNotContains(t, out, "2 Alice Bruxelles")
+}

+func TestPgCreateDatabase(t *testing.T) {
+	_ = testutil.SystemTest(t)
+	t.Parallel()
+
+	_, dbName, cleanup := initTest(t, randomID())
+	defer cleanup()
+
+	ctx, cancel := context.WithTimeout(context.Background(), time.Hour)
+	defer cancel()
+	out := runSampleWithContext(ctx, t, pgCreateDatabase, dbName, "failed to create a Spanner PG database")
+	assertContains(t, out, fmt.Sprintf("Created Spanner PostgreSQL database [%s]", dbName))
+}

### Release Notes

<details>
<summary>grpc/grpc-go</summary>

### [`v1.45.0`](https://togithub.com/grpc/grpc-go/releases/v1.45.0)

[Compare Source](https://togithub.com/grpc/grpc-go/compare/v1.44.0...v1.45.0)

### Bug Fixes

-   xds/clusterresolver: pass cluster name to DNS child policy to be used in creds handshake ([#​5119](https://togithub.com/grpc/grpc-go/issues/5119))
-   reflection: support dynamic messages ([#​5180](https://togithub.com/grpc/grpc-go/issues/5180))
    -   Special Thanks: [@​codebutler](https://togithub.com/codebutler)

### Performance Improvements

-   wrr: improve randomWRR performance ([#​5067](https://togithub.com/grpc/grpc-go/issues/5067))
    -   Special Thanks: [@​huangchong94](https://togithub.com/huangchong94)

### Behavior Changes

-   server: convert context errors returned by service handlers to status with the correct status code (`Canceled` or `DeadlineExceeded`), instead of `Unknown` ([#​5156](https://togithub.com/grpc/grpc-go/issues/5156))

### New Features

-   reflection: add `NewServer(ServerOptions)` for creating a reflection server with advanced customizations ([#​5197](https://togithub.com/grpc/grpc-go/issues/5197))
-   xds: support federation ([#​5128](https://togithub.com/grpc/grpc-go/issues/5128))
-   xds/resource: accept Self as LDS's RDS config source and CDS's EDS config source ([#​5152](https://togithub.com/grpc/grpc-go/issues/5152))
-   xds/bootstrap: add plugin system for credentials specified in bootstrap file ([#​5136](https://togithub.com/grpc/grpc-go/issues/5136))

</details>

### Release Notes

<details>
<summary>jhump/protoreflect</summary>

### [`v1.12.0`](https://togithub.com/jhump/protoreflect/releases/v1.12.0)

[Compare Source](https://togithub.com/jhump/protoreflect/compare/v1.11.0...v1.12.0)

This change includes a new feature related to source code information for compiled-in proto descriptors. It also includes some other bug fixes.

##### "github.com/jhump/protoreflect/desc"

Changes/fixes:

-   The `FindSymbol` method of `FileDescriptor` would panic if given an empty string as the symbol name. This has been fixed. This case now returns a nil descriptor, indicating no element with the given name could be found.
-   The various `Load*` functions will return descriptors that comment information (and the underlying `FileDescriptorProto` will contain source code info) is the `protoc-gen-gosrcinfo` plugin was used to generate additional Go code for these proto files.

##### "github.com/jhump/protoreflect/desc/protoprint"

Changes/fixes:

-   If an option included a message type, and was printed as a compact message literal, it had an errant extra space before the final closing '}' symbol. This is fixed, and these are now printed with a single space between the last field value and the closing brace.

##### "github.com/jhump/protoreflect/desc/sourceinfo"

This is a brand new package which allows for registering source code information for a proto source file. It also includes some API for using/querying the source code info. This is useful to retain comments for compiled and linked-in descriptors. It is not expected that users would explicitly register source code info; instead use the `protoc-gen-gosrcinfo` plugin, in addition to `protoc-gen-go`, when compiling your proto sources.

##### "github.com/jhump/protoreflect/desc/sourceinfo/cmd/protoc-gen-gosrcinfo"

This is a brand new command which is a `protoc` plugin for augmenting compiled and linked-in descriptors with source code information. When used, the `desc` package can include source code info (and thus comments) when loading linked-in descriptors. The `desc/sourceinfo` package can be used to query for the source code info and can be useful for integrating this data with other things, such as gRPC server reflection.

</details>

### Release Notes

<details>
<summary>jhump/protoreflect</summary>

### [`v1.12.0`](https://togithub.com/jhump/protoreflect/releases/v1.12.0)

[Compare Source](https://togithub.com/jhump/protoreflect/compare/v1.11.0...v1.12.0)

This change includes a new feature related to source code information for compiled-in proto descriptors. It also includes some other bug fixes.

##### "github.com/jhump/protoreflect/desc"

Changes/fixes:

-   The `FindSymbol` method of `FileDescriptor` would panic if given an empty string as the symbol name. This has been fixed. This case now returns a nil descriptor, indicating no element with the given name could be found.
-   The various `Load*` functions will return descriptors that comment information (and the underlying `FileDescriptorProto` will contain source code info) is the `protoc-gen-gosrcinfo` plugin was used to generate additional Go code for these proto files.

##### "github.com/jhump/protoreflect/desc/protoprint"

Changes/fixes:

-   If an option included a message type, and was printed as a compact message literal, it had an errant extra space before the final closing '}' symbol. This is fixed, and these are now printed with a single space between the last field value and the closing brace.

##### "github.com/jhump/protoreflect/desc/sourceinfo"

This is a brand new package which allows for registering source code information for a proto source file. It also includes some API for using/querying the source code info. This is useful to retain comments for compiled and linked-in descriptors. It is not expected that users would explicitly register source code info; instead use the `protoc-gen-gosrcinfo` plugin, in addition to `protoc-gen-go`, when compiling your proto sources.

##### "github.com/jhump/protoreflect/desc/sourceinfo/cmd/protoc-gen-gosrcinfo"

This is a brand new command which is a `protoc` plugin for augmenting compiled and linked-in descriptors with source code information. When used, the `desc` package can include source code info (and thus comments) when loading linked-in descriptors. The `desc/sourceinfo` package can be used to query for the source code info and can be useful for integrating this data with other things, such as gRPC server reflection.

</details>
